<subSubSection pageId="85" pageNumber="86" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="85.[151,1437,251,638]" pageId="85" pageNumber="86">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,251,277]" pageId="85" pageNumber="86">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This species is unique among the southern South American species in having a well-developed tooth anteriorly on the hypostomal carina. From 
<taxonomicName authority="Lepeco &amp; Gonçalves, 2020" authorityName="Lepeco &amp; Gonçalves" authorityYear="2020" box="[635,754,287,314]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Augochlora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="85" pageNumber="86" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mendax" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[635,754,287,314]" italics="true" pageId="85" pageNumber="86">A. mendax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[761,852,288,314]" pageId="85" pageNumber="86">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[761,852,288,314]" pageId="85" pageNumber="86" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
it can be separated also by the lack of a tuberculate elevation on S1 of females and clypeus apex without yellowish band on males. This species presents a strong pattern of head polymorphism on females, firstly observed by 
<bibRefCitation author="Sakagami, S. F. &amp; Moure, J. S." box="[765,1071,359,386]" pageId="85" pageNumber="86" pagination="303 - 313" refId="ref76634" refString="Sakagami, S. F. &amp; Moure, J. S. (1965) Cephalic polymorphism in some Neotropical halictine bees (Hymenoptera: Apoidea). Anais da Academia Brasileira de Ciencias, 37 (2), 303 - 313." type="journal article" year="1965">Sakagami &amp; Moure (1965)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="85" pageNumber="86" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="85.[151,1437,251,638]" pageId="85" pageNumber="86">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,395,421]" pageId="85" pageNumber="86">Comments.</emphasis>
For species description and comments on the 
<typeStatus box="[856,959,395,421]" pageId="85" pageNumber="86">lectotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Holmberg. Scale" authorityYear="1886" box="[997,1135,395,422]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Augochlora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="85" pageNumber="86" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="iphigenia">
<emphasis box="[997,1135,395,422]" italics="true" pageId="85" pageNumber="86">A. iphigenia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
see 
<bibRefCitation author="Dalmazzo, M. &amp; Roig-Alsina, A." pageId="85" pageNumber="86" pagination="15 - 32" refId="ref73683" refString="Dalmazzo, M. &amp; Roig-Alsina, A. (2011) Revision of the species of the New World genus Augochlora (Hymenoptera, Halictidae) occurring in the southern temperate areas of its range. Zootaxa, 2750, 15 - 32. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 2750.1.2" type="journal article" year="2011">Dalmazzo &amp; Roig-Alsina (2011)</bibRefCitation>
. Nests were studied by 
<bibRefCitation author="Sakagami, S. F. &amp; Moure, J. S." box="[554,864,431,458]" pageId="85" pageNumber="86" pagination="119 - 138" refId="ref76679" refString="Sakagami, S. F. &amp; Moure, J. S. (1967) Additional observations on the nesting habits of some Brazilian Halictine bees. Mushi, 40 (10), 119 - 138." type="journal article" year="1967">Sakagami &amp; Moure (1967)</bibRefCitation>
. For comments on head polymorphism of females see 
<bibRefCitation author="Sakagami, S. F. &amp; Moure, J. S." box="[194,500,467,494]" pageId="85" pageNumber="86" pagination="303 - 313" refId="ref76634" refString="Sakagami, S. F. &amp; Moure, J. S. (1965) Cephalic polymorphism in some Neotropical halictine bees (Hymenoptera: Apoidea). Anais da Academia Brasileira de Ciencias, 37 (2), 303 - 313." type="journal article" year="1965">Sakagami &amp; Moure (1965)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="85" pageNumber="86" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="85.[151,1437,251,638]" pageId="85" pageNumber="86">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,503,529]" pageId="85" pageNumber="86">Distribution.</emphasis>
This is a commonly collected species in Southern South America, occurring in the Brazilian states of Minas Gerais, Paraná, Rio Grande do Sul, Santa Catarina, and S„o Paulo. In 
<collectingCountry box="[1115,1226,539,565]" name="Argentina" pageId="85" pageNumber="86">Argentina</collectingCountry>
the species occurs in the provinces of 
<collectingRegion box="[370,523,575,602]" country="Argentina" name="Ciudad Autonoma de Buenos Aires" pageId="85" pageNumber="86">Buenos Aires</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[535,609,575,601]" country="Argentina" name="Chaco" pageId="85" pageNumber="86">Chaco</collectingRegion>
, Córdoba, 
<collectingRegion box="[733,855,576,602]" country="Argentina" name="Entre Rios" pageId="85" pageNumber="86">Entre Ríos</collectingRegion>
, Misiones, 
<collectingRegion box="[984,1043,575,601]" country="Argentina" name="Salta" pageId="85" pageNumber="86">Salta</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[1055,1156,575,602]" country="Argentina" name="San Luis" pageId="85" pageNumber="86">San Luis</collectingRegion>
, and 
<collectingRegion box="[1217,1318,576,602]" country="Argentina" name="Santa Fe" pageId="85" pageNumber="86">Santa Fé</collectingRegion>
. There are also records in 
<collectingCountry box="[321,425,612,638]" name="Paraguay" pageId="85" pageNumber="86">Paraguay</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[480,580,612,638]" name="Uruguay" pageId="85" pageNumber="86">Uruguay</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
